CD hydrogels were used as adsorbents for PFOS removal from water. The adsorption kinetics were studied under different conditions, including the solution pH, the initial concentration of PFOS ([PFOS]0), adsorbents with different CD content and different PEG/PPG ratio (Fig. 4
                        ). In most of the cases, the real-time adsorption amount (q
                        t) increases markedly within the initial 8 h, which reaches the equilibrium after ca. 20 h. It should be noticed here that hydrogel composed merely of PEG/PPG cannot adsorb PFOS. This points out that CD moieties in the hydrogels are the real residing sites of PFOS molecules.

CD66-0.2E/P with the largest adsorption capacity for PFOS was further tested for adsorbing the short-chain PFASs, including PFBS and PFHxS (Fig. 8
                        ). It is clear that q
                        m with both the units of mg/g and mmol/g decreases markedly upon decreasing the length of perfluoroalkyl chain, implying that CD66-0.2E/P prefers to adsorb the PFAS molecules with longer perfluoroalkyl chain. This can be ascribed to stronger hydrophobic interaction between longer perfluoroalkyl chains and CD moieties of hydrogels.
